NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Next let us talk about what Kia should lead. Normally leading an unprotected ace is a bad idea, so a diamond is probably not right. On the other hand, given I supported the suit, it is a little better than just leading some random unprotected ace. Regardless, I would not lead a diamond. Further, in general, leading away from an honor is an aggressive lead. It is high risk, high reward. |
PG| ***** 21 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So normally in suit contract, I don't lead away from an honor unless my partner has bid the suit or I think an attacking lead is called for. For example, I might think, based on the auction that dummy has a long running suit. So, normally I shy away from leading away from an honor. In this hand  trump lead is conceivable as a likely passive lead, although the auction does not particularly call for a trump lead. |
PG| ***** 22 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|So when I have nothing better to lead, I lead a suit with only small cards. As far as I am concerned, the longer the suit the better. Therefore, leading from a 4 or 5 card suit with no honor is best, leading from 3 small is ok, leading from a doubleton is not as desirable. Having said that, however, on this hand, I probably would choose a spade. but it is hardly clear. Here, any of the 4 suits could be right.|
