^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Now as to how the auction might go. Whenever it goes 1N-P-P-? you should strain to balance no matter how many points you have. The points will tend to be almost evenly spread out (although the NT bidder's side on average will have 21 or 22). In fact, it turns out, in 4th seat, you prefer having a weak hand to a strong hand. the reason is, your side has around 18-20. |
PG| ***** 53 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|If you have say 4 or 5, partner has 14 or so and partner is the one sitting behind the strong hand. Therefore, although it is far from obvious, the weaker your hand is, the more you should want to balance when the opponent opens 1N.|
PG| ***** 54 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|One another point. I would open 2@H with the West hand. Many people would not a) because of the 4 card spade suit and b) because they don't think their hearts are good enough. But, as most of you know, I think they are wrong. The 4-card major in particular is a "myth". There are very few hands where it is better to play in your 4-card suit when you have a 6-card suit. |
PG| ***** 55 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|And also, the reason I don't worry too much about the strength of my suit is because length in general is more important than strength. So pretty much any time I have 5-10 and a 6-card suit, I open a weak 2. But you have to decide what style suits you.|
